                  <msItem xml:id="coloph1">
                     <colophon>
                        <locus target="200vc"/>Fol. 200vc: ተፈጸመ፡ መጽሐፈ፡ ሃይማኖተ፡ አበው፡ በረድኤተ፡ አብ፡ ወወልድ፡ ወመንፈስ፡ ቅዱስ፤ ዘተወጥነ፡ በወርኃ፡ ጥምቀት[sic]፡ ተፈጸመ፡ በወርኃ፡ ግንቦት፡ በሠረቀ፡ መዓልት፡ ፳ወ፭፡ በሠረቀ፡ ሌሊት፡ ፳፡ በመንፈቀ፡ ፭፡ በጊዜ፡ ቀትር፡ እንዘ፡ ሀሎ፡ ፀሐይ፡ በማእከለ፡ ሰማይ፡ በመንግሥተ፡ ንጉሥ፡ ኢ&lt;…&gt;፡ ፲ወ፱፡ ወሊቀ፡ ጳጳሳት፡ አባ፡ ዮሐንስ፡ ወብፁዕ፡ ጳጳስነ፡ አባ፡ ማርቆስ፤ ወመምህረ፡ ደብር፡ አባ፡ ቄርሎስ፨ እም፡ ዓመተ፡ ዓለም በ፸፻፡ ፩፻፡ ፺ወ፫፡ በዘመነ፡ ማቴዎስ፡ ወንጌላዊ፨ ወዘአጽሐፎሂ፡ ክፍለ፡ ኢየሱስ፡ ወጸሐፊኒ፡ ኃጥእ፡ ወአባ፡ ገበረ፡ ክርስቶስ፤ ይጽሐፍ፡ ስሞሙ፡ ኀበ፡ ዓምደ፡ ወርቅ፡ በቀለመ፡ ጽድቅ፡ ኢየሱስ፡ ክርስቶስ፡ ሊቅ፡ ለዓለመ፡ ዓለም፡ አሜን፡ ወአሜን፡ ለይኩን፡ ለይኩን፨<foreign xml:lang="en">Fol. 200vc: The book “Faith of the Fathers” was completed with the help of the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit. It was commenced in the month of Ṭǝmqät [sic] and completed in the month of Gǝnbot, at the beginning of the day 25 and at the beginning of the night 20, in mänfäqä 5, at midday, when the sun was in the middle of the sky, during the reign of King ʾI&lt;…&gt; 19 and Patriarch ʾabba Yoḥannǝs and our blessed Metropolitan ʾabba Marqos and mämhǝrä däbr ʾabba Qerlos. From the year of the world 7193, in the year of Matthew the Evangelist. And the one who caused it to be written is Kǝflä ʾIyäsus and the scribe is sinful ʾabba Gäbrä Krǝstos. May Jesus Christ, the Master, write their names on the golden pillar with the ink of the righteousness; forever and ever; Amen and Amen; so be it, so be it.</foreign>
                        <note>The colophon contains only the first letter of the name of the king (“i”), the other letters have been erased. Since also two other names are mentioned, i.e., Patriarch of Alexandria Yoḥannǝs XVI (in tenure 1676–1718) and the Ethiopian Metropolitan Marqos IV (arrived in Ethiopia in 1689, d. 1716), it may be inferred that the king meant is ʾIyasu I (r. 1682-1706). The completion of the writing is dated to 7193 (“year of the world”, = 1693 A.D., cp. ChChron). Kǝflä ʾIyäsus is said to be the commissioner, and ʾabba Gäbrä Krǝstos is the scribe. ʾAbba Qerlos appears to be the head of an unnamed church or monastery.</note>
                     </colophon>
